        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName>16 Granville Place</placeName>
                    <date>6 July 1874</date>
                    <salute>My dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>I will take the earliest opportunity of trying the experiments you suggest; which so far from being superfluous are of great interest: If any other should occur to you please let me know and I will as far as possible, make them.<ref target="#foot.f1"/> I will give D<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Brunton your message the next time I see him.<ref target="#foot.f2"/></p>
<p>I am sending you a copy of my book on the poisonous Snakes of India to look at. Any time when you are coming to London will be time enough to return it.<ref target="#foot.f3"/> I should be gratified to know that you thought it of use— The object is set forth in the preface.<ref target="#foot.f4"/> I worked at the subject for about 4 years &amp; thus I presented the work to the Govt of India for the benefit of the country— It is now distributed throughout great part of India &amp; will I hope do good</p>
<p>Yours very truly | J. Fayrer</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-9533.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to Joseph Fayrer, 4 July [1874]</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-9533.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to Joseph Fayrer, 4 July [1874]</ref> and nn. 5 and 6. Fayrer refers to <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_693.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Thomas Lauder Brunton</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">A new, expanded edition of Fayrer’s book, <hi rend="italic">Thanatophidia of India</hi> (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_2474.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Fayrer 1872</ref>), was published in February 1874 (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_2475.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Fayrer 1874</ref>; see <hi rend="italic">Publishers’ circular</hi>, 2 March 1874, p. 138). CD was in London briefly for the wedding of <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1222.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Francis Darwin</ref> and Amy Ruck on 23 July 1874; his next visit to London was from 3 to 12 December 1874 (see ‘Journal’ (Appendix II)).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f4">Fayrer wrote that the object of his book was to supply reliable information on the venomous snakes of India (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_2474.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Fayrer 1872</ref>, p. vii).</note>
        </div>        
            
